🔹 Problems with Traditional String Concatenation

Old way of creating strings:

const name = "Rahul";
const age = 25;

const message = "Hello, my name is " + name + " and I am " + age + " years old.";
console.log(message);
❌ Issues:
Hard to read with many variables
Messy when creating multi-line strings
Error-prone when adding lots of dynamic data
🔹 Template Literal Syntax
Use backticks ` instead of quotes
Embed variables with ${}
Supports multi-line strings natively
const name = "Rahul";
const age = 25;

const message = `Hello, my name is ${name} and I am ${age} years old.`;
console.log(message);
✅ Output:
Hello, my name is Rahul and I am 25 years old.


🔹 Multi-Line Strings

Old way:

const message = "Line 1\n" +
                "Line 2\n" +
                "Line 3";
console.log(message);

Template literals:

const message = `Line 1
Line 2
Line 3`;
console.log(message);
✅ Output:
Line 1
Line 2
Line 3


🔹 Embedding Expressions

You can include any expression inside ${}:

const a = 5;
const b = 10;

console.log(`The sum of ${a} and ${b} is ${a + b}.`);
✅ Output:
The sum of 5 and 10 is 15.

🔹 Use Cases in Modern JavaScript
Dynamic content in web pages
Multi-line HTML templates
Logging messages with variables
String interpolation in functions


| Feature     | Old Concatenation       | Template Literal       |
| ----------- | ----------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Variables   | `"Hello " + name + "!"` | `` `Hello ${name}!` `` |
| Multi-line  | `"Line 1\nLine 2"`      | `` `Line 1\nLine 2` `` |
| Expressions | `"Sum: " + (a + b)`     | `` `Sum: ${a + b}` ``  |
| Readability | ❌ messy                 | ✅ clean & readable     |

Key Takeaways
Template literals = backticks + ${} interpolation
Supports multi-line strings
Improves readability and reduces errors
Widely used in modern JS, especially for dynamic content


